### 1. Task outcome (short version):
The short-term causes of World War I include the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand, the subsequent July Crisis involving diplomatic tensions between Austria-Hungary and Serbia, and the mobilization of major powers resulting from alliances.
### 2. Task outcome (extremely detailed version):
The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria on June 28, 1914, served as the immediate catalyst for World War I. Following this event, Austria-Hungary issued an ultimatum to Serbia, demanding compliance on several points within a short timeframe. When Serbia responded by agreeing to most demands but rejecting key ones involving Austrian oversight, Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia on July 28. This initiation of hostilities triggered a chain reaction due to the complex system of alliances in place at the time. In the days following the declaration of war, Russia mobilized its forces in support of Serbia, leading Germany to declare war on Russia, and subsequently on France. The July Crisis involved a series of diplomatic failures and escalatory actions among the major powers, ultimately leading to a full-scale war by early August 1914.
The role of alliances was crucial; Austria-Hungary was backed by Germany (the Central Powers), while Russia had the support of France and Britain (the Allies). The interlinked nature of these alliances ensured that a conflict between two nations quickly escalated into a war involving multiple countries across Europe. The atmosphere of nationalism, militarism, and accumulated grievances among European nations also significantly contributed to the fragility of peace, making the outbreak of war more likely.
### 3. Additional context (if relevant):
The assassination of Franz Ferdinand not only served as the spark but also intensified existing nationalistic sentiments within Europe. The failure of diplomatic channels during the July Crisis highlighted the volatility of the geopolitical landscape at that time, and the rapid mobilization of military forces illustrated the embrace of military solutions over diplomatic ones. The resulting conflict would reshape international relations and have lasting impacts on global politics.